IP Camera
A surveillance camera that operates over an internet protocol network, often having
limitations on simultaneous streaming connections.
Article 4: Time Synchronization Issues Impacting Images
Title: How-To Ensure Correct Time Synchronization to Prevent Image Issues
Quick Checklist:
Check device time and time zone settings, ensuring they match the platform (e.g., CET).
Verify that DST (Daylight Saving Time) is enabled if the device uses NTP server sync.
Confirm if any unexpected change in time or configuration occurred around a daylight savings time shift.
Note the one-hour time offset often seen with Hi Vision devices, which may not always be a problem, unlike with other device types like Dahua.
In-Depth Guide:
Time synchronization problems are a critical factor that can lead to missing or incorrect alarm images. When time settings are misaligned, the system struggles to accurately locate and retrieve
the correct image clip corresponding to the alarm event.
Mandatory Time Settings and Checks
1. Time Zone Alignment:
Always ensure the time zone settings on the physical device (e.g., Hi Vision) match the configured time zone on the platform (Genesis).
Time zone discrepancies are the 100% reason for receiving wrong images.
2. Daylight Saving Time (DST) Configuration:
It is mandatory to enable DST on the device, particularly if the device uses an NTP server for time synchronization.
If DST is unchecked, the system may work fine for half the year but will fail or stop working correctly when the daylight changes (time shift) occur. If the customer performs a manu
3. Impact on Image Retrieval:
If the time zone is configured incorrectly, you will typically receive either incorrect alarm images (e.g., from the past or future) or no image at all.
Even minor time sync errors (e.g., exceeding the platform's 5-second tolerance) can drastically reduce the effective length of the recorded video clip, making it difficult to successfully
4. Device-Specific Considerations:
When troubleshooting Hi Vision devices, be aware that they may show a one-hour time offset. This offset is often a historical quirk and may not signify a problem.
However, if this one-hour offset appears on devices like Dahua, it indicates a time synchronization issue that the customer must resolve.
Related Phrases (Glossary):
Term
Definition
DST
Daylight Saving Time; must be enabled on devices using NTP sync to prevent time
failure during time shifts.
NTP
Server
Network Time Protocol server, used to automatically sync device time.
Time Zone
The geographic configuration used to maintain time standards; mismatch in this setting
often results in wrong alarm images.
